ter 13. Sacred or Dissident: Islam, Embodiment, and Subjectivity on Post-Revolutionary Iranian Theatrical Stage -- tChapter 14. Public Pleasures: Negotiating Gender and Morality through Syrian Popular Dance -- tPart V. Global Flows of Popular Culture in the Muslim World -- tChapter 15. Performing Islam around the Indian Ocean Basin: Musical Ritual and Recreation in Indonesia and the Sultanate of Oman -- tChapter 16. Muslims, Music, and Religious Tolerance in Egypt and Ghana: A Comparative Perspective on Difference -- tChapter 17. Music Festivals in Pakistan and England -- tChapter 18. Fleas in the Sheepskin: Glocalization and Cosmopolitanism in Moroccan Hip-Hop -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPopular culture serves as a fresh and revealing window on contemporary developments in the Muslim world because it is a site where many important and controversial issues are explored and debated. Aesthetic expression has become intertwined with politics and religion due to the uprisings of the “Arab Spring,” while, at the same time, Islamist authorities are showing increasingly accommodating and populist attitudes toward popular culture. Not simply a “westernizing” or “secularizing” force, as some have asserted, popular culture now plays a growing role in defining what it means to be Muslim. With well-structured chapters that explain key concepts clearly, Islam and Popular Culture addresses new trends and developments that merge popular arts and Islam. Its eighteen case studies by eminent scholars cover a wide range of topics, such as lifestyle, dress, revolutionary street theater, graffiti, popular music, poetry, television drama, visual culture, and dance throughout the Muslim world from Indonesia, Africa, and the Middle East to Europe. The first comprehensive overview of this important subject, Islam and Popular Culture offers essential new ways of understanding the diverse religious discourses and pious ethics expressed in popular art productions, the cultural politics of states and movements, and the global flows of popular culture in the Muslim world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aIslam and culturezIslamic countriesy20th century. 0aIslam and culturezIslamic countriesy21st century. 0aIslam and culture--Islamic countries--20th century. 0aIslam in mass media. 0aPopular culturezIslamic countries. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh1 aAlagha, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrishkopf, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodgson, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapchan, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaan, Nina ter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeVine, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeVine, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeftahi, Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNieuwkerk, Karin van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNooshin, Laudan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtterbeck, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRasmussen, Anne K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds, Bryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalamandra, Christa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalois, Kendra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/